ğŸ“Œ What is Quick Sort?
Quick Sort is a divide and conquer algorithm that selects a pivot element and partitions the array into two parts:
ğŸ”¹ Left Subarray â†’ Elements smaller than the pivot
ğŸ”¹ Right Subarray â†’ Elements greater than the pivot
It then recursively sorts both subarrays and combines them!

ğŸ› ï¸ Quick Sort in JavaScript

function quickSort(array) {
    if (array.length < 2) {
        return array; // Base case
    }

    let pivot = array[array.length - 1]; // Choosing the last element as pivot
    let left = [];
    let right = [];

    for (let i = 0; i < array.length - 1; i++) {
        if (array[i] < pivot) {
            left.push(array[i]); // Elements smaller than pivot
        } else {
            right.push(array[i]); // Elements greater than pivot
        }
    }

    return [...quickSort(left), pivot, ...quickSort(right)];
}

const arr = [999, 45, -54, 549, -7, 75];
console.log(quickSort(arr));  
// Output: [-54, -7, 45, 75, 549, 999]
ğŸ§ How Does Quick Sort Work? (Step-by-Step Example)
For array = [5, 3, 8, 1] with pivot = 1

1ï¸âƒ£ Partition â†’ Left [ ], Pivot 1, Right [5, 3, 8]
2ï¸âƒ£ Recursive sort â†’ Left remains empty, Right [5, 3, 8] â†’ Pivot = 8
3ï¸âƒ£ New Left [5, 3], Pivot 8, Right [ ]
4ï¸âƒ£ Recursive sort â†’ [3, 5] sorted
âœ… Final Output: [1, 3, 5, 8]

â³ Understanding Time Complexity
ğŸ”¹ Best & Average Case: O(n log n) â€“ Efficient for large datasets.
ğŸ”¹ Worst Case: O(nÂ²) â€“ If the smallest or largest element is always chosen as the pivot (can be optimized).

ğŸ’¡ Quick Sort is widely used due to its efficiency and in-place sorting capability!

ğŸ’¡ Key Takeaways
âœ” Faster than Bubble & Insertion Sort for large datasets
âœ” Uses divide and conquer for better efficiency
âœ” Time Complexity: O(n log n) in the average case
âœ” Not a stable sort (doesnâ€™t maintain relative order of equal elements)

